# Harness 100 Cursor Optimization Rule

Apply this rule when creating or updating harness workflows in this repository.

## Core policy

- Use Cursor-native patterns first (`Agent`, `Plan`, `Task`, Subagents, MCP).
- Keep orchestration explicit: phases, dependencies, and parallel branches.
- Prefer reusable instructions in rules and harness docs over one-off prompt text.

## Mode strategy

- Use `Plan` mode for large, multi-file, or architecture-level changes.
- Use `Agent` mode for implementation after the plan is validated.
- Keep tasks scoped so each mode switch is intentional and reviewable.

## Subagent strategy

- Delegate context-heavy work (codebase exploration, shell-heavy execution, browser workflows) to subagents.
- Run independent subagent workstreams in parallel when outputs do not depend on each other.
- Return concise synthesized results to parent flow (avoid raw log dumping).

## Rules and context strategy

- Store project behavior in `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`.
- Use `@` references (`@file`, `@folder`, `@rule`) to inject context instead of long inline prompt duplication.
- Keep rules focused and composable; split large guidance into multiple rules.

## MCP strategy

- Prefer MCP tools/resources when external systems or live data are involved.
- Document required MCP dependencies and fallback behavior when MCP is unavailable.
- Keep deterministic output formats for MCP-backed tasks.

## Harness authoring standards

- Every orchestrator skill should define:
  - phase-by-phase execution,
  - dependency DAG,
  - parallelizable branches,
  - failure and retry handling,
  - reduced-scope execution modes.
- Reviewer agents should validate cross-file consistency and actionable fixes.

## Anti-patterns

- Do not rely on Claude-specific terminology or file layouts.
- Do not require monolithic prompts when rules or subagents can modularize work.
- Do not mix unrelated objectives into one unscoped execution phase.
